# gen115 (L15): the first deliberate mid-turn TOOL CALL — the honest seam
# between "reason" and "act". A word-count question can't be answered by lookup
# or inference, so the brain COMPILES it to a real command and INVOKES a
# deterministic oracle (the pure POSIX pipeline simulator — no subprocess), then
# folds the computed result back, naming the exact command it ran so the call is
# observable, not a stubbed constant. Held-out text transfers because the count
# is PRODUCED by the oracle, never stored.

# Six words, counted by the tool.
> how many words in: the cat sat on the mat
< 6. (I ran the tool: echo the cat sat on the mat | wc -w.)

# Held-out text (different length) — the count is computed, not memorized.
> how many words in: a b c d e f g
< 7. (I ran the tool: echo a b c d e f g | wc -w.)

# A different cue phrasing reaches the same tool.
> count the words in: one two three
< 3. (I ran the tool: echo one two three | wc -w.)

# Anti-impostor: the oracle is real and pure — punctuation it cannot safely run
# is declined honestly, never faked.
> how many words in: hello, world!
< I can only count plain words for now (letters and digits, no punctuation).